Main analysis: 500 simulated gene sets and 1000 simulated brain data with moranâ€™s I centered around 0.03, rdonors>0.4

0. Setup

code_path='F:/Google Drive/post-doc/vitural_histology_revisit/new_code' # path to the code
simRes_path=file.path(code_path, 'sim_res_raw') # path to the simulated data

gene_set_type='RandomSet500_int' # gene set type: 500 simulated gene sets
gene_data_type='abagen_r04' # AHBA data type rdonors>0.4
brain_data_type= 'random_spatial003' # 1000 simulated brain data with moran's I centered around 0.03

1. Load functions

library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
source(file.path(code_path,'analysis_functions.R'))
source(file.path(code_path,'data_functions.R'))
source(file.path(code_path,'spatial_functions.R'))
source(file.path(code_path,'cor_functions.R'))

2. Load simulated data

#analysis.path=file.path(result.path,'analysis_with_sim')
#dir.create(analysis.path)

# get the list of csv files
res.files=list(
  spin_brain=paste0('Res_', gene_set_type, '_', gene_data_type, '_', brain_data_type, '_spin_brain_5000_sim1000.csv'),
  random_gene=paste0('Res_', gene_set_type, '_', gene_data_type, '_', brain_data_type, '_random_gene_5000_sim1000.csv'))

# get the full path of res.files
res2read=lapply(res.files, function(x) list.files(simRes_path, pattern=x, recursive =T, full.names=T))

# read res.files
res.df.list=lapply(res2read, read.csv, stringsAsFactors = F)

3. Psig-G analysis

# Extract pvals and group them by geneSet 
# Psig-G is calculated for each gene set
nest_by='geneSet'
pvals.nested=lapply(res.df.list, get_pvals_nested, nest_by=nest_by, heat_plot=F)
psig.list=lapply(pvals.nested, get_psig, if_fdr=F)

3.1.Plot Psig-G

Figure 2. A. Probability of significance for each gene set (Psig-G). B. Mean value and standard error (i.e., standard deviation/âˆš500) of Psig-G across all the gene sets.

p1=plot_raw_psig_list(psig.list,show_shuffle = F, ylab2show = 'Psig-G', title2show = 'A.',title_adj = -0.07)
p2=plot_summary_psig_list(psig.list,show_shuffle = F, ylab2show = 'Psig-G',title2show = 'B.',title_adj = -0.1)
grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=1)

3.2.Examining the correlation between co-expression and Psig-G

coexp_info=get_geneSetList_info(data_path=file.path(code_path, 'data'), geneSet_type=gene_set_type, geneData_type=gene_data_type)
coexp_res.nested.list=lapply(psig.list, correlate_psig_with_info, info=coexp_info,var2test='coexp_mean')
coexp_res.report.list=lapply(coexp_res.nested.list, report_res.nested)
coexp_res.plot.list=lapply(coexp_res.nested.list, plot_res.nested, annot_position=c(-0.05,0.5))

3.2.1. Plot correlation between co-expression and Psig-G

Figure 3. Results of co-expression analysis for the competetive (A) and self-contained null models (B). The x-axis indicates the co-expression of a specific gene set and the y-axis indicates the probability of significance for a specific gene set (Psig-G). Each dot denotes a specific gene set with the lighter color denoting the larger size of the gene set. The horizontal dashed line denotes a Psig-G of 0.05. To alleviate overplotting, a small random noise is added to the dots.

p3=grid.arrange(grobs=coexp_res.plot.list$random_gene,
                ncol=2,
                top = textGrob("A. Competetive null models",gp=gpar(fontsize=16,font=1),x = -0.01, hjust = 0),
                left =textGrob("Psig-G",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2),rot=90),
                bottom=textGrob("Co-expression",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2)))
p4=grid.arrange(grobs=coexp_res.plot.list$spin_brain,
                ncol=2,
                top = textGrob("B. Self-contained null models",gp=gpar(fontsize=16,font=1),x = -0.01, hjust = 0),
                left =textGrob("Psig-G",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2),rot=90),
                bottom=textGrob("Co-expression",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2)))
grid.arrange(p3,p4)

4. Psig-B analysis

4.1. Plot Psig-B

Figure 4. A. Probability of significance for each simulated brain map (Psig-B). B. Mean value and standard error (i.e., standard deviation/âˆš1000) of Psig-B across all the simulated brain maps.

p1=plot_raw_psig_list(psig.list,show_shuffle = F, ylab2show = 'Psig-B', title2show = 'A.',title_adj = -0.086)
p2=plot_summary_psig_list(psig.list,show_shuffle = F, ylab2show='Psig-B',title2show = 'B.',title_adj = -0.10)
grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=1)

4.2. Examine the correlation between BI-dip and Psig-B

# `var2test='pos_neg_dist'` is for BI-dist `var2test='modetest_stat'` is for BI-dip. default method is dip test
brain_info=get_brain_info(data_path=file.path(code_path, 'data'), brainData_type = brain_data_type, geneData_type = gene_data_type) 
brain_res.nested.list=lapply(psig.list, correlate_psig_with_info,info=brain_info,var2test='modetest_stat')
brain_res.report.list=lapply(brain_res.nested.list, report_res.nested)
brain_res.plot.list=lapply(brain_res.nested.list,plot_res.nested,
                           annot_position=c(-0.016,0.95),
                           xlim2show=c(-0.03,0.06),
                           ylim2show=c(-0.05,1))

4.2.1. Plot correlation between Psig-B and BI-dip

Figure 5. Results of the bimodality analysis for the competitive (A) and self-contained null models (B). The x-axis indicates the bimodality of the correlations between a specific brain map and transcriptional profiles of background genes, which was measured using the dip test statistic. The y-axis indicates the probability of significance for a specific brain map (Psig-B). Each dot denotes a brain map and the horizontal dashed line denotes a Psig-B value of 0.05. To alleviate overplotting, a small random noise is added to the dots.

p3=grid.arrange(grobs=brain_res.plot.list$random_gene,
                ncol=2,
                top = textGrob("A. Competetive null models",gp=gpar(fontsize=16,font=1),x = -0.01, hjust = 0),
                left =textGrob("Psig-B",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2),rot=90),

                ncol=2,

4.3.1. Plot correlation between Psig-B and BI-dist

Figure S7. Results of bimodality analysis for the competitive (A) and self-contained null models (B).The x-axis indicates the bimodality of the correlations between a specific brain map and transcriptional profiles of background genes. The distance between the positive and negative modes of the correlations was used as an indicator of the bimodality. The y-axis indicates the probability of observing significant correlations for a specific brain map (Psig-B). Each dot represents a simulated brain map and the horizontal dashed line denotes Psig=0.05. To alleviate overplotting, a small random noise is added to the dots.

p3=grid.arrange(grobs=brain_res.plot.list$random_gene,
                ncol=2,

                left =textGrob("Psig-B",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2),rot=90),
                bottom=textGrob("Bimodality",gp=gpar(fontsize=12,font=2)))
p4=grid.arrange(grobs=brain_res.plot.list$spin_brain,
